HEADWORD: Paleography
<hw>Pa`le*og"ra*phy</hw>
<pr>(p⟦amac⟧`l⟦esl⟧*⟦ocr⟧g"r⟦adot⟧*f⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[<ets>Paleo-</ets> + <ets>-graphy</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>pal⟦eacute⟧ographie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An ancient
manner of writing; ancient writings, collectively; <as>as, Punic
<ex>paleography</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The study of ancient inscriptions and modes of
writing; the art or science of deciphering ancient writings, and
determining their origin, period, etc., from external characters;
diplomatics.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Paleola</ent>⟦br⟧
